@end multitable

@noindent
A useful rule of thumb: if the model response @emph{begins} with anything
other than @samp{@{}, the planner will fail.  Thinking tokens always appear
before the JSON.


@node Quantization
@section Quantization: Squeezing a 7B Model into 4.7 GB
@cindex quantization
@cindex Q4_K_M
@cindex GGUF quantization
@cindex floating-point precision

@dfn{Quantization} is the process of reducing the precision of a model's
weights from the full-precision format used during training to a smaller
format that fits on consumer hardware.

@subsection Full-precision baseline

During training, model weights are typically stored as @dfn{BF16} or
@dfn{FP16} --- 16-bit floating-point numbers (2 bytes per weight).  A 7B
parameter model requires about @strong{13 GB} in FP16.  A 3B model requires
about @strong{6 GB}.  Neither fits comfortably in 16 GB of RAM alongside the
OS and other applications.

@subsection How Q4_K_M works

@samp{Q4_K_M} is a GGUF quantization format developed for the llama.cpp
project.  Let us break down the name:

@table @strong
@item Q
Quantized format (as opposed to F16 or F32 full precision).

@item 4
Target storage of approximately @strong{4 bits per weight} (compared to 16
bits in FP16).

@item K
Uses the @dfn{k-quant} method: instead of a single global scale factor per
tensor, each @strong{block of 64 weights} gets its own scale factor and
zero-point.  This preserves local structure much better than uniform
quantization.

@item M
Medium precision tier within k-quants.  Attention layers (more sensitive to
precision loss) are stored at slightly higher bit depth; feed-forward layers
(more tolerant) are compressed more aggressively.  The result is an
@emph{average} of approximately @strong{4.5 bits per weight} --- not a pure 4.
@end table

@noindent
Visualized:

@example
FP16 weight:  [1111000011110000]   16 bits, exact
Q4 weight:    [1111]               4 bits, approximate

Per-block (64 weights) in K-quant:
  [scale_factor][zero_point][w0_4bit][w1_4bit]...[w63_4bit]
  The scale and zero-point allow recovery: actual ≈ w_4bit × scale + zero
@end example

@subsection Memory savings and accuracy impact

Measured on llama.cpp benchmarks for a 7B model:

@multitable @columnfractions .15 .15 .20 .50
@headitem Format @tab Bits/wt @tab File size @tab Perplexity increase vs FP16
@item FP16 @tab 16 @tab 13.0 GB @tab baseline (perfect)
@item Q8_0 @tab 8 @tab 6.7 GB @tab +0.0004 (undetectable)
@item Q6_K @tab ~6.5 @tab 5.15 GB @tab +0.004 (negligible)
@item Q5_K_M @tab ~5.5 @tab 4.45 GB @tab +0.014 (tiny)
@item @strong{Q4_K_M} @tab @strong{~4.5} @tab @strong{3.8 GB} @tab @strong{+0.05 (imperceptible)}
@item Q3_K_M @tab ~3.5 @tab 3.3 GB @tab +0.15 (noticeable)
@item Q2_K @tab ~2.5 @tab 2.6 GB @tab +0.6 (significant)
@end multitable

@noindent
@dfn{Perplexity} is a measure of how surprised the model is by text it
should predict well --- lower is better.  The +0.05 increase at Q4_K_M is
so small that no practical code generation task is affected.

@subsection Why quantization also speeds up generation

Generation speed is memory-bandwidth-bound: the CPU must read model weights
from RAM into registers on every forward pass.  Smaller weights mean less
data transferred per step:

@example
FP16, 7B model: 13 GB of weights to stream per forward pass step
Q4_K_M, 7B model: 3.8 GB of weights to stream per forward pass step
                   = 3.4× less data = ~3× faster generation
@end example

@noindent
Practical result on an i7-8550U:

@example
qwen2.5-coder:7b-instruct-q4_K_M  → ~2--5 t/s   (generation)
qwen2.5-coder:3b-instruct-q4_K_M  → ~5--15 t/s  (generation)
@end example

@noindent
The 3B model generates faster than the 7B because both the weight reads
@emph{and} the matrix multiplications are cheaper for the smaller model.


@node Codebud Lifecycle Implementation
@section What Codebud Does at Each Phase
@cindex Codebud implementation details
@cindex AgentCore
@cindex llm_stub.py

The table below maps each lifecycle phase to the Codebud code that handles
it.

@multitable @columnfractions .20 .40 .40
@headitem Phase @tab Codebud code @tab Notes
@item Pre-warm @tab @code{agent/llm_stub.py::prewarm_model()} @tab Fires in background thread at AgentCore init
@item Tokenization @tab Ollama internal (GGUF embedded tokenizer) @tab Codebud does not touch this layer
@item Prefill @tab @code{agent/llm_stub.py::_call_ollama()} starts the POST request @tab @code{on_chunk} receives nothing during this phase
@item First token @tab @code{ProgressIndicator.on_chunk()} called for the first time @tab Spinner switches from ``prefill'' to ``generating'' display
@item Generation @tab @code{_call_ollama()} iterates @code{r.iter_lines()} @tab Each line is one NDJSON token fragment
@item Streaming @tab @code{on_chunk} callback passed through AgentCore → LLMPlanner → call_llm @tab Decouples display from LLM layer
@item Done signal @tab @code{chunk.get("done")} breaks the loop @tab Full text assembled from @code{chunks}
@item JSON parse @tab @code{LLMPlanner._attempt()} calls @code{json.loads()} @tab On failure: strips fences, retries with simpler prompt
@item Idle / heartbeat @tab @code{agent/llm_stub.py::ModelHeartbeat._ping()} @tab Sends ``hi'' every 4 min to reset keep_alive timer
@item Unload @tab @code{agent/core.py::AgentCore.close()} stops heartbeat @tab Model unloads naturally after next keep_alive expiry
@end multitable

@noindent
The complete call chain for a single user request:

@example
run_agent.py cmd_run / cmd_chat
  → AgentCore.handle_user_message(message, on_chunk=prog.on_chunk)
      → LLMPlanner.generate_plan(message, on_chunk=on_chunk)
          → LLMPlanner._build_prompt(message)   [tokenization input]
          → call_llm(prompt, on_chunk=on_chunk)
              → _call_ollama(model, prompt, timeout, on_chunk)
                  ← Ollama /api/generate  (streaming NDJSON)
                      Phase 1: tokenize prompt
                      Phase 2: prefill (KV cache built)
                      Phase 3+4: generate + stream tokens
                  → on_chunk(fragment)  [ProgressIndicator.on_chunk]
          → json.loads(full_output)
          → _validate_plan_structure(plan_json)
      → AgentCore._validate_plan(plan_json)
  → Executor.execute_plan(plan)
      → ToolRegistry.get(tool).run(args)
      → MemoryStore.add_snapshot(step, result)
  → print results
@end example


