@node References and Further Reading
@section References and Further Reading
@cindex references
@cindex bibliography

The claims and technical details in this chapter are drawn from the
following primary sources.  Readers wishing to verify a specific claim or
study a topic in more depth should consult these directly.

@subsection Transformer Architecture and Attention

@table @strong

@item Vaswani et al. (2017) --- @emph{Attention Is All You Need}
The original paper introducing the transformer architecture, scaled
dot-product attention, multi-head attention, and the encoder-decoder
structure.  The KV cache and the prefill/decode split originate from this
work.
@*@url{https://arxiv.org/abs/1706.03762}

@item Radford et al. (2019) --- @emph{Language Models are Unsupervised Multitask Learners} (GPT-2)
Introduced byte-level BPE tokenization for large language models and
demonstrated scaling behaviour.
@*@url{https://cdn.openai.com/better-language-models/language_models_are_unsupervised_multitask_learners.pdf}

@end table

@subsection Quantization

@table @strong

@item Frantar et al. (2022) --- @emph{GPTQ: Accurate Post-Training Quantization for Generative Pre-trained Transformers}
The quantization method underlying many GGUF 4-bit formats.
@*@url{https://arxiv.org/abs/2210.17323}

@item llama.cpp GGUF format specification and k-quant implementation
The definitive reference for GGUF encoding, the Q4_K_M block format,
scale and zero-point layout, and the mixed-precision approach for
attention vs. feed-forward layers.
@*@url{https://github.com/ggml-org/llama.cpp/blob/master/docs/gguf.md}
@*@url{https://github.com/ggml-org/llama.cpp/pull/1684} (k-quants PR)

@item Dettmers et al. (2022) --- @emph{LLM.int8(): 8-bit Matrix Multiplication for Transformers at Scale}
Foundational work on weight quantization for inference; motivates the
per-block scale approach used in k-quants.
@*@url{https://arxiv.org/abs/2208.07339}

@item Comparative quantization benchmarks (perplexity and speed)
@*@url{https://github.com/ggml-org/llama.cpp/discussions/406}

@end table

@subsection Tokenization and BPE

@table @strong

@item Sennrich et al. (2016) --- @emph{Neural Machine Translation of Rare Words with Subword Units}
The paper that adapted BPE from text compression to NLP tokenization.
@*@url{https://arxiv.org/abs/1508.07909}

@item HuggingFace NLP Course --- @emph{Byte-Pair Encoding tokenization}
The clearest accessible explanation of the BPE training and inference
algorithms, with worked examples.
@*@url{https://huggingface.co/learn/llm-course/chapter6/5}

@item Qwen2.5-Coder Technical Report (2024)
Documents the 151,646-token vocabulary, training corpus (5.5T tokens),
and special token IDs for Qwen2.5-Coder models.
@*@url{https://arxiv.org/html/2409.12186v2}

@end table

@subsection Prefill, Decode, and KV Cache

@table @strong

@item Pope et al. (2022) --- @emph{Efficiently Scaling Transformer Inference}
Introduces the prefill/decode split as a distinct systems-level concept and
analyses the memory-bandwidth bottleneck in the decode phase.
@*@url{https://arxiv.org/abs/2211.05102}

@item NVIDIA Developer Blog --- @emph{Mastering LLM Techniques: Inference Optimization}
Comprehensive treatment of TTFT, ITL, batch sizing, KV cache strategies, and
quantization for GPU inference.
@*@url{https://developer.nvidia.com/blog/mastering-llm-techniques-inference-optimization/}

@item Redis Engineering Blog --- @emph{Prefill vs. Decode: Understanding LLM Inference Performance}
Accessible explanation of the compute-vs-memory-bandwidth distinction between
the two phases, with workload classification.
@*@url{https://redis.io/blog/prefill-vs-decode/}

@item Liu et al. (2023) --- @emph{Ring Attention with Blockwise Transformers}
Analysis of O(N@sup{2}) attention complexity and methods to reduce it.
@*@url{https://arxiv.org/abs/2310.01889}

@end table

